          "code": "2.13",
          "order": 12,
          "title": "Short-Circuit Evaluation",
          "goal": "Understand how <b>&&</b> and <b>||</b> stop early, and use it to write safer conditions.",
          "blocks": [
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "When Java evaluates a combined condition, it is lazy in a useful way: it stops as soon as the answer is certain. This is called <strong>short-circuit evaluation</strong>, and once you know it, you can order conditions to prevent errors."
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "How it works"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "For <code>&&</code> (AND): if the left side is <strong>false</strong>, the whole thing is already false, so Java doesn't even look at the right side. For <code>||</code> (OR): if the left side is <strong>true</strong>, the whole thing is already true, so the right side is skipped."
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "int x = 0;\n\n// Left side is false, so the right side (x > 0) is never checked:\nif (x != 0 && (10 / x) > 1) {\n    System.out.println(\"safe\");\n} else {\n    System.out.println(\"skipped the risky division\");\n}",
              "out": "skipped the risky division"
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "Why it matters: guarding against errors"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "The example above is the key idea. Dividing by zero crashes a program. By checking <code>x != 0</code> <strong>first</strong> and joining with <code>&&</code>, you guarantee the risky <code>10 / x</code> only runs when <code>x</code> is safe — because if <code>x</code> is 0, short-circuiting skips the division entirely. The <strong>order of your conditions</strong> becomes a safety tool."
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "String s = \"\";\n// Check length is > 0 before touching character 0:\nif (s.length() > 0 && s.charAt(0) == 'A') {\n    System.out.println(\"starts with A\");\n} else {\n    System.out.println(\"empty or doesn't start with A\");\n}",
              "out": "empty or doesn't start with A"
            },
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "kind": "note",
              "title": "The rule to remember",
              "html": "Put the <strong>cheap or protective check first</strong>, and the risky one second, joined by <code>&&</code>. That way the risky part only runs when it's safe. This is one of the most practical habits in all of programming."
            },
            {
              "type": "check",
              "items": [
                [
                  "In <code>a && b</code>, when is <code>b</code> skipped?",
                  "When <code>a</code> is false — the result is already false."
                ],
                [
                  "In <code>a || b</code>, when is <code>b</code> skipped?",
                  "When <code>a</code> is true — the result is already true."
                ],
                [
                  "How does short-circuiting let you avoid dividing by zero?",
                  "Check <code>x != 0</code> first with <code>&&</code>; if x is 0 the division on the right is never evaluated."
                ]
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "exercise",
              "html": "Read an integer <code>d</code>. Print \"ok\" only if <code>d</code> is not zero AND <code>100 / d</code> is greater than 5 — ordering the conditions so the division is safe.",
              "meta": "stdin: one integer · checks: no crash on 0"
            }
          ],
          "exercise": {},
          "quizBank": []
        },
        {
          "code": "2.14",
          "order": 13,
          "title": "De Morgan's Laws",
          "goal": "Rewrite negated conditions cleanly by distributing a <b>!</b> across <b>&&</b> and <b>||</b>.",
          "blocks": [
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "Sometimes you write a condition for the opposite case — \"if it is <em>not</em> the case that both X and Y.\" Negating a combined condition can be confusing. <strong>De Morgan's Laws</strong> are two simple rules that let you push a <code>!</code> inward and turn a tangled negation into something readable."
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "The two laws"
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "!(a && b)   is the same as   !a || !b\n!(a || b)   is the same as   !a && !b",
              "out": ""
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "In words: <strong>distribute the NOT to each part, and flip the operator</strong> — AND becomes OR, OR becomes AND. \"Not (A and B)\" means \"not-A or not-B.\" \"Not (A or B)\" means \"not-A and not-B.\""
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "A concrete example"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "Say a form is valid only when the name is filled in AND the age is at least 18. The <em>invalid</em> case is the negation:"
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "boolean nameFilled = false;\nboolean adult = true;\n\n// \"not valid\" — two equivalent ways:\nboolean invalidA = !(nameFilled && adult);\nboolean invalidB = !nameFilled || !adult;   // De Morgan's\n\nSystem.out.println(invalidA);   // true\nSystem.out.println(invalidB);   // true — same result",
              "out": "true\ntrue"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "Both say the same thing: the form is invalid if the name is missing <strong>or</strong> the person isn't an adult. The second version is often easier to read and reason about."
            },
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "kind": "note",
              "title": "Why learn this?",
              "html": "Beyond simplifying code, De Morgan's Laws help you avoid a classic bug: incorrectly negating a condition. When you flip a condition, you must flip <em>both</em> the comparisons <em>and</em> the connector. <code>!(x &gt; 0 && x &lt; 10)</code> is <code>x &lt;= 0 || x &gt;= 10</code> — note every piece changed."
            },
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "kind": "mistake",
              "title": "Common beginner mistake",
              "html": "<strong>Forgetting to flip the operator:</strong> students often negate each part but leave <code>&&</code> as <code>&&</code>. <code>!(a && b)</code> is <strong>not</strong> <code>!a && !b</code> — the AND must become OR. Change all three things: each condition and the connector."
            },
            {
              "type": "check",
              "items": [
                [
                  "Rewrite <code>!(a || b)</code> without the outer NOT.",
                  "<code>!a && !b</code> — distribute the NOT and turn OR into AND."
                ],
                [
                  "What is <code>!(x &gt;= 5 && x &lt;= 10)</code> as a positive condition?",
                  "<code>x &lt; 5 || x &gt; 10</code> — flip each comparison and change AND to OR."
                ],
                [
                  "When you distribute a NOT across &&, what does && become?",
                  "OR (<code>||</code>)."
                ]
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "exercise",
              "html": "A user may enter only if they have a ticket AND are over 12. Read the two facts and print, using De Morgan's form (<code>!hasTicket || age &lt;= 12</code>), whether they must be turned away.",
              "meta": "checks: correct rejection logic"
            }
          ],
          "exercise": {},
          "quizBank": []
        },
        {
          "code": "2.15",
          "order": 14,
          "title": "Strings",
          "goal": "Work with text as <b>String</b> values — building them, measuring them, and comparing them correctly.",
          "blocks": [
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "A <strong>String</strong> is a sequence of characters — a piece of text like <code>\"hello\"</code> or <code>\"Ava123\"</code>. You have used Strings since lesson 2.1; now we look at what you can actually <em>do</em> with them. (Unit 3 goes deeper into String methods; this is the foundation.)"
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "Making and joining Strings"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "You create a String with double quotes, and join Strings (or a String and a value) with <code>+</code> — <strong>concatenation</strong>."
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "String first = \"Ada\";\nString last = \"Lovelace\";\nString full = first + \" \" + last;\nSystem.out.println(full);\nSystem.out.println(\"Length: \" + full.length());",
              "out": "Ada Lovelace\nLength: 12"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "Notice <code>full.length()</code> — a <strong>method</strong> that asks the String how many characters it holds (spaces count). The dot means \"ask this String to do something.\" You will meet many more String methods in Unit 3."
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "Reaching a single character"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "Characters in a String have <strong>positions</strong>, numbered from <strong>0</strong>. <code>charAt(i)</code> gives the character at position <code>i</code>."
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "String word = \"Java\";\nSystem.out.println(word.charAt(0));   // J  (position 0, not 1)\nSystem.out.println(word.charAt(3));   // a",
              "out": "J\na"
            },
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "kind": "note",
              "title": "Counting from zero",
              "html": "This trips up everyone at first: the first character is at position <strong>0</strong>, so in <code>\"Java\"</code> (length 4) the valid positions are 0, 1, 2, 3. Position 4 does not exist and would cause an error. Zero-based counting returns constantly in Unit 5 with arrays."
            },
            {
              "type": "heading",
              "text": "Comparing Strings — the .equals rule again"
            },
            {
              "type": "prose",
              "html": "Worth repeating because it matters so much: to check whether two Strings hold the same text, use <code>.equals</code>, not <code>==</code>."
            },
            {
              "type": "code",
              "code": "String pw = \"secret\";\nSystem.out.println(pw.equals(\"secret\"));         // true\nSystem.out.println(pw.equalsIgnoreCase(\"SECRET\")); // true",
              "out": "true\ntrue"
            },
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "kind": "note",
              "title": "Strings don't change",
              "html": "A String is <strong>immutable</strong> — methods like these never alter the original; they return a new value. <code>pw.toUpperCase()</code> gives back \"SECRET\" but leaves <code>pw</code> as \"secret\" unless you store the result. Keep this in mind as you learn more String methods."
            },
            {
              "type": "callout",
              "kind": "mistake",
              "title": "Common beginner mistakes",
              "html": "<strong>Comparing with <code>==</code>:</strong> use <code>.equals</code> for text. <strong>Off-by-one on charAt:</strong> the last valid position is <code>length() - 1</code>, not <code>length()</code>. <strong>Expecting a method to modify the String:</strong> Strings are immutable — capture the returned value."
            },
            {
              "type": "check",
              "items": [
                [
                  "What does <code>\"hello\".length()</code> return?",
                  "5."
                ],
                [
                  "What is the position of the first character in a String?",
                  "0 — positions are zero-based."
                ],
                [
                  "How do you correctly check if String <code>s</code> equals \"done\"?",
                  "<code>s.equals(\"done\")</code>."
                ]
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "exercise",
              "html": "Read a line of text and print its length and its first character. Then print whether it equals \"hello\" (case-insensitive).",
              "meta": "stdin: a line of text · checks: length, first char, equality"
            }
          ],
          "exercise": {},
          "quizBank": []
        }
      ]
